[[File:Escherichia coli.jpg|thumb|229x229px|''[[Escherichia coli]]'' is a neutrophilic organism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fda.gov/Food/FoodScienceResearch/SafePracticesforFoodProcesses/ucm094145.htm|title=Safe Practices for Food Processes - Evaluation and Definition of Potentially Hazardous Foods - Chapter 3. Factors that Influence Microbial Growth|last=Nutrition|first=Center for Food Safety and Applied|website=www.fda.gov|language=en|access-date=2016-11-03}}</ref>]]
A '''neutrophile''' is a neutrophilic [[organism]]<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gJWKBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA68&lpg=PA68&dq=where+to+find+information+on+neutrophilic+organisms+AND+pH&source=bl&ots=5uW_BQS3-7&sig=lX6dNm-jphh79C8TlsAB2bE-y3s&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjAzNjJhfbPAhUGjz4KHQTAAPgQ6AEIVDAJ#v=onepage&q=where%20to%20find%20information%20on%20neutrophilic%20organisms%20AND%20pH&f=false|title=Microbiology for Nurses|last=Parvathi|first=V. Deepa|publisher=Pearson Education India|isbn=9789332540668|language=en}}</ref> that thrives in a neutral [[pH]] environment between 6.5 and 7.5.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=Microbiology: An introduction|last=Tortora, Funke, Case|first=|publisher=Benjamin-Cummings Publishing Company, Subs of Addison Wesley Longman, Inc|year=2015|isbn=0321929152|location=|pages=152|quote=|via=}}</ref>

==Environment==
The pH of the environment can support growth or hinder neutrophilic organisms.  When the pH is within the microbe's range, they grow and within that range there is an optimal growth pH.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=http://www.brooklyn.cuny.edu/bc/ahp/CellBio/Growth/MGpH.html|title=Properties of Microbes|website=www.brooklyn.cuny.edu|access-date=2016-11-01}}</ref>  Neutrophiles are adapted to live in an environment where the hydrogen ion concentration is at equilibrium.<ref name=":1" />  They are sensitive to the concentration, and when the pH become too basic or acidic, the cell's proteins can [[Denaturation (biochemistry)|denature]].<ref name=":2" />  Depending on the microbe and the pH, the microbe's growth can be slowed or stopped altogether.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fda.gov/Food/FoodScienceResearch/SafePracticesforFoodProcesses/ucm094145.htm|title=Safe Practices for Food Processes - Evaluation and Definition of Potentially Hazardous Foods - Chapter 3. Factors that Influence Microbial Growth|last=Nutrition|first=Center for Food Safety and Applied|website=www.fda.gov|language=en|access-date=2016-11-01}}</ref>  Manipulation of the pH of the environment that the microbe is in is used by the food industry to control its growth in order to increase the [[shelf life]] of food.<ref name=":3" />

